23–":"1323–Afdød","1323–Female":"1323–Afdød","1387–1433":"1387–1433","1343–Female":"1343–Afdød","–1459":"–1459","1357–Male":"1357–Afdød","1303–Female":"1303–Afdød","1459":"1459","1303":"1303","about 1429":"omkring 1429","1357":"1357","1323":"1323","1433":"1433","1343":"1343","1387":"1387","about 1343":"omkring 1343",", Leicestershire, , England":"Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom",", Chester, England":"Chester, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Lea, Cheshire, England":"Lea by Backford, Cheshire, England"},"nl":{"1323–":"1323–Overleden","1323–Female":"1323–Overleden","1387–1433":"1387–1433","1343–Female":"1343–Overleden","–1459":"–1459","1357–Male":"1357–Overleden","1303–Female":"1303–Overleden","1459":"1459","1303":"1303","about 1429":"circa 1429","1357":"1357","1323":"1323","1433":"1433","1343":"1343","1387":"1387","about 1343":"circa 1343",", Leicestershire, , England":"Leicestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk",", Chester, England":"Chester, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Lea, Cheshire, England":"Lea by Backford, Cheshire, England"},"en":{"1323–":"1323–Deceased","1323–Female":"1323–Deceased","1387–1433":"1387–1433","1343–Female":"1343–Deceased","–1459":"–1459","1357–Male":"1357–Deceased","1303–Female":"1303–Deceased","1459":"1459","1303":"1303","about 1429":"about 1429","1357":"1357","1323":"1323","1433":"1433","1343":"1343","1387":"1387","about 1343":"about 1343",", Leicestershire, , England":"Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom",", Chester, England":"Chester, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Lea, Cheshire, England":"Lea by Backford, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Huberk","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Lucien, Armand, Normand, Olivier, Adlore, Alphonse, Andre, Benoit, Camil, Camille, Fernand.","German, Dutch, English, French, Walloon, Breton, Polish, Czech, Slovak, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. The name was borne by an 8th-century Christian saint, bishop of Maastricht, who was adopted as the patron of hunters, and helped to increase the popularity of the personal name, especially in the Low Countries.","History: Jean-François-Barthélemi Hubert from Granville in Manche, France, married Félicité Arsenault in Havre-Aubert, QC, in 1801. Nicolas Hubert <i>dit</i> Lacroix from France married Marguerite Landreau in France <i>c.</i> 1653, died in Montreal, QC, in 1687. René Hubert from Paris, France, married Françoise (de) Lacroix in Quebec City, QC, in 1669. Pierre-Paul Hébert/Hubert from France married Suzanne Laporte in QC <i>c.</i> 1716. — This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."],"variants":[{"name":"Haubrich","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Gunter, Kurt, Lothar.","German and Dutch: variant of   Hubert  ."]},{"name":"Hipp","meanings":["South German: metonymic occupational name for a baker of waffles, from Middle High German <i>hippe</i> ‘waffle’.","South German: from a short form of   Hubert  , also spelled <b>Hüpp</b> (see   Hupp  ).","German: from a short form of an ancient Germanic name with the first element <i>hild</i> ‘strife, battle’ and a second element beginning with <i>b-</i> (for example <i>Hildibald</i>, <i>Hildibrand</i>)."]},{"name":"Haubert","meanings":["German: variant of   Hubert  .","French: from the personal name <i>Aubert</i>, a late medieval form of an ancient Germanic compound name, <i>Adalberht</i> (see   Albert  ).","French: perhaps a metonymic occupational name for someone who made or wore a mailcoat, French <i>haubert</i>, from Old French <i>halberc</i>, <i>hauberc</i>."]},{"name":"Haupert","meanings":["German: variant of   Hubert  ."]},{"name":"Hoppert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Bernt.  German Kurt, Otto.","South German: variant of   Hubert  ."]},{"name":"Hobin","meanings":["Walloon and northern French: from a vernacular pet form of the personal name   Hubert  . This surname is rare in France.","Irish: variant of   Hoban  ."]},{"name":"Hobert","meanings":["German and Dutch: variant of   Hubert  ."]},{"name":"Hubbard","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, from the Norman French personal name   Hubert   (ancient Germanic <i>Hugibert</i>, composed of elements meaning ‘mind, spirit’ and ‘bright’)."]},{"name":"Hoben","meanings":["German: patronymic from a short form of   Hubert  ."]},{"name":"Hotz","meanings":["South German and Swiss German: from thieves' cant for a peasant or farmer, which in turn derives from an ancient Germanic personal name, <i>Hugizo</i> or <i>Huzo</i>, pet forms of a compound name formed with <i>hug-</i> as the first element (see, for example,   Hubert  ,   Hugh  ).","South German: possibly a nickname from Middle High German <i>hotzen</i> ‘to run swiftly’."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Maud Huberk was born in 1323, in Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir Henry Hubeck, was -34 and her mother, Joan Barnack, was 20. She married Hugh Calveley II about 1429, in Chester, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter."},"et":{"1323–":"1323–Surnud","1323–Female":"1323–Surnud","1387–1433":"1387–1433","1343–Female":"1343–Surnud","–1459":"–1459","1357–Male":"1357–Surnud","1303–Female":"1303–Surnud","1459":"1459","1303":"1303","about 1429":"umbes 1429","1357":"1357","1323":"1323","1433":"1433","1343":"1343","1387":"1387","about 1343":"umbes 1343",", Leicestershire, , England":"Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom",", Chester, England":"Chester, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lea, Cheshire, England":"Lea by Backford, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"1323–":"1323–Kuollut","1323–Female":"1323–Kuollut","1387–1433":"1387–1433","1343–Female":"1343–Kuollut","–1459":"–1459","1357–Male":"1357–Kuollut","1303–Female":"1303–Kuollut","1459":"1459","1303":"1303","about 1429":"noin 1429","1357":"1357","1323":"1323","1433":"1433","1343":"1343","1387":"1387","about 1343":"noin 1343",", Leicestershire, , England":"Leicestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta",", Chester, England":"Chester, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lea, Cheshire, England":"Lea by Backford, Cheshire, England"},"fr":{"1323–":"1323–Décédée","1323–Female":"1323–Décédée","1387–1433":"1387–1433","1343–Female":"1343–Décédée","–1459":"–1459","1357–Male":"1357–Décédé","1303–Female":"1303–Décédée","1459":"1459","1303":"1303","about 1429":"environ 1429","1357":"1357","1323":"1323","1433":"1433","1343":"1343","1387":"1387","about 1343":"environ 1343",", Leicestershire, , England":"Leicestershire,